After briefly analyzing based on your comments, I do agree with you, this does not appear to an exploitable vulnerability for those using this library as intended.  The POC above relies on calling the embedded ply functions, not the intended interfaces for this library.  Therefore, we will not publish security alerts.

I will also add, we typically do not do analysis like this to determine the legitimacy of a particular CVE.  That said, case was helpful for us to clarify some guidelines on what CVEs we do publish.  Thanks again!

Hi @CaineInc!

The natural sort function is always expecting string values, since it shouldn't encounter them if the parser is set as "text". I didn't do this because any extra operations within the sort function would only slow the process down. It may only be a minimal slowing, but that sometimes makes a big difference in IE.

Anyway, If you are using a custom parser, make sure the type is set as "numeric":

```js
$.tablesorter.addParser({
  id: 'number',
  is: function(s, table, cell, $cell) {
    // return false so this parser is not auto detected
    return false;
  },
  format: function(s, table, cell, cellIndex) {
    return parseFloat(s);
  },
  // set type, either numeric or text
  type: 'numeric'
});
```

Or, make sure to set the column parser as a digit:

```html
<th class="sorter-digit">Values</th>
```

